. Short Interest Ratio (Days-to-Cover) = short interest / avg daily volume (e.g. >5 days is high risk
reddit.com
).	T-1 Close (uses prior data)	A crowded short can be rocket fuel. Heavily shorted stocks are paradoxically prone to rise – any upward price pressure forces shorts to buy-to-cover, driving a self-reinforcing squeeze
investopedia.com
investopedia.com
. A high Days-to-Cover means shorts would need days of normal volume to exit – if volume spikes (and price rises), many shorts panic-buy simultaneously, causing rapid gains. This was the recipe behind meme stock squeezes
reddit.com
.	Data lag: short interest is reported biweekly (FINRA), so it may be outdated. A stock might have squeezed yesterday (shorts already covered) but you’re viewing old SI%. Also, not every high SI stock squeezes – some stay flat or drop if no bullish catalyst emerges (shorts might be correct about poor fundamentals). A general market downtrend can override a squeeze setup (shorts stay in control).
Hard-to-Borrow & Fee	Short borrow fee rate (annualized %) and/or shortable shares availability from broker (IBKR). E.g. fee > 20% or “HTB” (hard-to-borrow) status = significant shorting constraints.	T-1 Close (fee from prior day; updates daily)	A skyrocketing borrow fee or scarcity of shares to short indicates high shorting demand and limited supply to short. When fees are high, short sellers are literally paying a premium to stay short – a sign of potential squeeze pressure. Often, just before major squeezes, borrow rates jump and availability dwindles, reflecting increased risk for shorts
reddit.com
. In a rally, shorts may hit risk limits faster if borrow cost is huge, leading to forced covering.	Sometimes borrow fees spike due to technical reasons (share recall, etc.) unrelated to an imminent squeeze. Also, a stock can have high short interest but still be easy to borrow (if float is large), meaning this signal is less useful for liquid large-caps. If fee data is stale or intraday changes occur, one might miss rapid shifts.
Prior Squeeze Setup	Prior-day momentum + high short: e.g. stock was up significantly on prior day on high volume, and still had high short interest remaining. (This indicates a possible Day 2+ squeeze continuation as not all shorts exited).	T-1 Close	Squeezes often extend over multiple days if shorts haven’t fully covered. A stock that jumped yesterday (say +15%) on volume, with high short interest, may see a “second leg” as shorts who survived Day 1 feel the pain on Day 2 (especially if the price breaks yesterday’s high). This signal combines momentum + short distress. It’s essentially setting up a squeeze extension play: today’s top gainer might be yesterday’s runner with shorts still trapped.	Overnight offerings/news can spoil a second-day rally (e.g. company uses the high price to announce a dilution – killing the momentum). Also, some Day2 moves fizzle if the catalyst was one-time (traders move on). If the stock gapped down in the morning (profit-taking or bad news), the squeeze may have already climaxed.
